<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1896-01-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1896-01-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="712" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d712">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Olney</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Terrell</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1896-01-02"><hi rend="italic">January 2,
                                1896</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Your 725 shows that promised protection was not given to American
                            citizens at Cæsarea until danger was virtually over. Represent this <pb facs="0705" n="1439" xml:id="pg_1439"/> strongly, and ask signal
                            rebuke of delinquent officer and peremptory orders for instant
                            protection in any threatened quarter at the first sign of disturbance.
                            The assurances of the Porte must be supported in fact in order to
                            satisfy this Government.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Olney.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>